merly Yes 94.5, a radio station in Myrtle Beach, South Carolina, US\n* [[Y.E.S. 93.3FM]], a Singaporean radio station\n\n==Music==\n===Groups===\n* [[Yes (band)]], an English rock band\n* [[Yes Featuring Jon Anderson, Trevor Rabin, Rick Wakeman]], an English rock band\n\n===Musicals and operetta===\n*[[Yes (musical)|''Yes'' (musical)]] 1928, Maurice Yvain\n\n===Albums===\n* [[Yes (Yes album)|''Yes'' (Yes album)]], by rock band Yes, 1969\n* ''[[The Yes Album]]'', by rock band Yes, 1971\n* [[Yes (Alvin Slaughter album)|''Yes'' (Alvin Slaughter album)]]\n* [[Yes! (Chad Brock album)|''Yes!'' (Chad Brock album)]]\n* [[Yes! (Jason Mraz album)|''Yes!'' (Jason Mraz album)]], 2014\n* [[Yes! (k-os album)|''Yes!'' (k-os album)]], 2009\n* [[Yes (Mika Nakashima album)|''Yes'' (Mika Nakashima album)]]\n* [[Yes (Morphine album)|''Yes'' (Morphine album)]], 1995\n* [[Yes (Pet Shop Boys album)|''Yes'' (Pet Shop Boys album)]], 2009\n* ''Yes!'', classical album by [[Julie Fuchs]] 2015\n* ''[[Yes L.A.]]'', 1979 punk rock compilation EP\n\n===Songs===\n* \"Yes!\" by [[Amber_(singer)|Amber]], 2002\n* [[Yes! (Chad Brock song)|\"Yes!\" (Chad Brock song)]], 2000\n* [[Yes (Coldplay song)|\"Yes\" (Coldplay song)]], 2008\n* [[Yes (LMFAO song)|\"Yes\" (LMFAO song)]], 2009\n* [[Yes (McAlmont & Butler song)|\"Yes\" (McAlmont & Butler song)]], 1995\n* [[Yes (Sam Feldt song)|\"Yes\" (Sam Feldt song)]], 2017\n* \"Yes\", from Black Sheep's 1991 studio album, [[A Wolf in Sheep's Clothing (Black Sheep album)|''A Wolf In Sheep's Clothing'']]\n* \"Yes\", from Demi Lovato's 2015 studio album, ''[[Confident (album)|Confident]]''\n* \"Yes\", from Maurice Yvain's 1928 musical, [[Yes (musical)|''Yes'']]\n* \"Yes\", from the [[Dirty Dancing (soundtrack)|''Dirty Dancing'']] film soundtrack\n* \"YES\", by [[Louisa Johnson]] featuring 2 Chainz, 2018\n*\"Yes\", by [[Beyonc\u00e9]], 2003\n*\"Yes\", by [[Billy Swan]], 1983\n*\"Yes\", by [[Connie Cato]], 1975\n*\"Yes\", by [[Cornell Campbell]], 1974\n*\"Yes\", by [[Dee C. Lee]], 1984\n*\"Yes\", by [[Demi Lovato]], 2015\n*\"Yes\", by [[The Family (band)|The Family]], 1985\n*\"Yes\", by [[Grapefruit (band)|Grapefruit]], 1968\n*\"Yes\", by [[Jay & The Americans]], 1962\n*\"Yes\", by [[Johnny Sandon]] And The Remo Four, 1963\n*\"Yes\", by [[Karl Wolf]] feat. Super Sako, Deena, Fito Blanko, 2019\n*\"Yes\", by [[Manic Street Preachers]], 1994\n*\"Yes\", by [[Merry Clayton]], 1988\n*\"Yes\", by [[Peppino Di Capri]]\t1962\n*\"Yes\", by [[Pet Shop Boys]], 2009\n*\"Yes\", by [[Roy Orbison]], 1983\n*\"Yes\", by [[Schaffer the Darklord]], 2015\n*\"Yes\", by [[Tim Moore (singer-songwriter)|Tim Moore]], 1985\n\n==See also==\n* {{lookfrom| Yes}}\n* [[Yesss (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{disambiguation}}\n", "text_old": "{{wiktionary|yes}}\n'''Yes''' or '''YES''' may refer to:\n* An affirmative particle in the English language; see [[yes and no]]\n\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==Education==\n* [[YES Prep Public Schools]], Houston, Texas, US\n* [[YES (Your Extraordinary Saturday)]], a learning program from the Minnesota Institute for Talented Youth\n* [[Young Eisner Scholars]], in Los Angeles, New York City, Chicago, and Appalachia, US\n* [[Young Epidemiology Scholars]], US\n\n==Technology==\n* [[yes (Unix)]], command to output \"y\" or a string repeatedly\n* [[Philips :YES]], a 1985 home computer\n* [[Yes! Roadster]], a German sports car\n\n==Transportation==\n* [[Yasuj Airport]], Iran, IATA airport code\n* YES Airways, later [[OLT Express]], Poland\n\n==Organization==\n* [[Yale Entrepreneurial Society]], US\n* [[YES Snowboards]]\n* [[The YES! Association]], a Swedish artist collective\n* [[Yes! Youth Movement]], Russia\n* [[Young European Socialists]] formally ECOSY\n* [[Youth Empowerment Scheme]], a children's charity, Belfast, Northern Ireland\n* [[Youth Energy Squad (Y.E.S)]]\n* [[Youth Entrepreneurship and Sustainability]]\n* [[YES (Lithuanian political party)]]\n\n==Literature==\n* [[Yes! (Hong Kong magazine)|''Yes!'' (Hong Kong magazine)]]\n* [[Yes! (U.S. magazine)|''Yes!'' (U.S. magazine)]], a magazine focused on social justice and sustainability\n* [[Yes! (Philippine magazine)|''Yes!'' (Philippine magazine)]], a showbiz-oriented magazine\n* [[Yes (novel)|''Yes'' (novel)]], a 1978 novel by Thomas Bernhard\n* ''Yes: My Improbable Journey to the Main Event of WrestleMania'', by Bryan Danielson, also known as [[Daniel Bryan]]\n\n==Film, television and radio==\n* [[Yes (film)|''Yes'' (film)]], a 2004 film by Sally Potter\n* [[yes (Israel)]], an Israeli satellite television provider\n* [[YES Network]], Yankees Entertainment and Sports Network\n* [[Yes TV]], a Canadian religious television system\n\n===Radio stations===\n* [[WTKN]], formerly Yes 94.5, a radio station in Myrtle Beach, South Carolina, US\n* [[Y.E.S. 93.3FM]], a Singaporean radio station\n\n==Music==\n===Groups===\n* [[Yes (band)]], an English rock band\n* [[Yes Featuring Jon Anderson, Trevor Rabin, Rick Wakeman]], an English rock band\n\n===Musicals and operetta===\n*[[Yes (musical)|''Yes'' (musical)]] 1928, Maurice Yvain\n\n===Albums===\n* [[Yes (Yes album)|''Yes'' (Yes album)]], by rock band Yes, 1969\n* ''[[The Yes Album]]'', by rock band Yes, 1971\n* [[Yes (Alvin Slaughter album)|''Yes'' (Alvin Slaughter album)]]\n* [[Yes! (Chad Brock album)|''Yes!'' (Chad Brock album)]]\n* [[Yes! (Jason Mraz album)|''Yes!'' (Jason Mraz album)]], 2014\n* [[Yes! (k-os album)|''Yes!'' (k-os album)]], 2009\n* [[Yes (Mika Nakashima album)|''Yes'' (Mika Nakashima album)]]\n* [[Yes (Morphine album)|''Yes'' (Morphine album)]], 1995\n* [[Yes (Pet Shop Boys album)|''Yes'' (Pet Shop Boys album)]], 2009\n* ''Yes!'', classical album by [[Julie Fuchs]] 2015\n* ''[[Yes L.A.]]'', 1979 punk rock compilation EP\n\n===Songs===\n* \"Yes!\" by [[Amber_(singer)|Amber]], 2002\n* [[Yes! (Chad Brock song)|\"Yes!\" (Chad Brock song)]], 2000\n* [[Yes (Coldplay song)|\"Yes\" (Coldplay song)]], 2008\n* [[Yes (LMFAO song)|\"Yes\" (LMFAO song)]], 2009\n* [[Yes (McAlmont & Butler song)|\"Yes\" (McAlmont & Butler song)]], 1995\n* [[Yes (Sam Feldt song)|\"Yes\" (Sam Feldt song)]], 2017\n* \"Yes\", from Black Sheep's 1991 studio album, [[A Wolf in Sheep's Clothing (Black Sheep album)|''A Wolf In Sheep's Clothing'']]\n* \"Yes\", from Demi Lovato's 2015 studio album, ''[[Confident (album)|Confident]]''\n* \"Yes\", from Maurice Yvain's 1928 musical, [[Yes (musical)|''Yes'']]\n* \"Yes\", from the [[Dirty Dancing (soundtrack)|''Dirty Dancing'']] film soundtrack\n* \"YES\", by [[Louisa Johnson]] featuring 2 Chainz, 2018\n*\"Yes\", by [[Beyonc\u00e9]], 2003\n*\"Yes\", by [[Billy Swan]], 1983\n*\"Yes\", by [[Connie Cato]], 1975\n*\"Yes\", by [[Cornell Campbell]], 1974\n*\"Yes\", by [[Dee C. Lee]], 1984\n*\"Yes\", by [[Demi Lovato]], 2015\n*\"Yes\", by [[The Family (band)|The Family]], 1985\n*\"Yes\", by [[Grapefruit (band)|Grapefruit]], 1968\n*\"Yes\", by [[Jay & The Americans]], 1962\n*\"Yes\", by [[Johnny Sandon]] And The Remo Four, 1963\n*\"Yes\", by [[Karl Wolf]] feat. Super Sako, Deena, Fito Blanko, 2019\n*\"Yes\", by [[Manic Street Preachers]], 1994\n*\"Yes\", by [[Merry Clayton]], 1988\n*\"Yes\", by [[Peppino Di Capri]]\t1962\n*\"Yes\", by [[Pet Shop Boys]], 2009\n*\"Yes\", by [[Roy Orbison]], 1983\n*\"Yes\", by [[Schaffer the Darklord]], 2015\n*\"Yes\", by [[Tim Moore (singer-songwriter)|Tim Moore]], 1985\n\n==See also==\n* {{lookfrom| Yes}}\n* [[Yesss (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{disambiguation}}\n", "name_user": "Favonian", "label": "safe", "comment": "padlock", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yes"}
{"title_page": "Munchkin cat", "text_new": "{{Infobox Catbreed\n<!-- Put article text AFTER this infobox markup. See: -->\n<!-- Wikipedia:WikiProject Cats/Templates for more info.-->\n| name          = Munchkin\n| image         = Longhairedmunchkin.jpg\n| imagecaption  = An adolescent munchkin kitten.\n| altname       =    <!-- separate multiple entries with <br /> -->\n| nickname      =    <!-- separate multiple entries with <br /> -->\n| country       = [[United States]]\n| cfastd        =\n| acfastd       =\n| ticastd       =https://tica.org/phocadownload/mk.pdf\n| ccastd        =\n| acfstd        =\n| gccfstd       =\n| fifestd       =\n| otherstd      =\n| notrecognized =\n| extinct       =\n| note          = \n|}}\n\nThe '''Munchkin cat''' or '''Sausage cat'''<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.peta.org/blog/sausage-cats/|title=\u2018Sausage Cat\u2019 Breed Not Trendy, Just the Result of Cruelty|date=2017-02-10|work=PETA|access-date=2018-07-17|url-status=live|language=en-US}}</ref> is a newer [[breed of cat]] characterized by its [[Dwarf |very short legs]], which are caused by a natural [[genetic mutation]]. The Munchkin is considered to be the original breed of [[dwarf cat]]. \n\nMuch controversy erupted over the breed when it was recognized by [[The International Cat Association]] (TICA) in 1995 with critics voicing concern over potential health and mobility issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2017/01/31/vets-warn-trend-for-sausage-cats-is-cruel-6416755/|title=Vets warn trend for sausage cats is cruel|last=|first=|date=2017-01-31|website=Metro UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> [[Governing Council of the Cat Fancy]] has not recognized it as a [[standardised breed]].\n\nThe name \"[[munchkin]]\" derives from writer [[L. Frank Baum]]'s diminutive inhabitants of [[Munchkin Country]], originating in the 1900 novel, ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Munchkin & Midget Cat Breed Facts|url=https://www.petmd.com/cat/breeds/c_ct_munchkin|website=www.petmd.com|publisher=petMD, LLC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Nunn|first1=Lyn|title=Munchkin Cats - Origin and History|url=http://www.catbreedsjunction.com/munchkin-cats.html|website=Cat Breeds Junction|accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fawcett|first1=Kirstin|title=7 Short Facts About Munchkin Cats|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/80011/7-short-facts-about-munchkin-cats|website=[[Mental Floss]]|accessdate=8 December 2017|language=en|date=3 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n=== Breed creation ===\nShort-legged cats have been documented a number of times around the world since the 1940s. A British veterinary report in 1944 noted four generations of short-legged cats which were similar to normal cats except for the length of the legs. This line disappeared during the Second World War but other short-legged cats were spotted in Russia during 1956 and the United States in the 1970s.<ref name=\"TICAintro\">{{cite web|url=https://tica.org/munchkin-breeders?view=article&id=857:munchkin-breed&catid=79|title=Munchkin Breed|date=13 August 2018|website=The International Cat Association (TICA)|publisher=The International Cat Association (TICA)|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, Sandra Hochenedel, a music teacher in [[Rayville, Louisiana|Rayville]], [[Louisiana]], found two pregnant cats who had been chased under a truck by a dog.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=coXIF8WbEKEC&dq|title=100 Cats Who Changed Civilization: History's Most Influential Felines|last=Stall|first=Sam|publisher=Quirk Books|year=2007|isbn=9781594741630|location=Philadelphia, PA|pages=20\u201322|via=Google Books}}</ref> She kept one of the cats and named her Blackberry and half of her kittens were born short-legged. Hochenedel gave a short-legged male kitten from one of Blackberry's litters to a friend, Kay LaFrance of [[Monroe, Louisiana|Monroe]], Louisiana, and she named the kitten Toulouse.<ref name=\":0\" /> It is from Blackberry and Toulouse's litter that today's Munchkin breed is descended.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Registry history of Munchkin breed ===\nThe Munchkin cat was first introduced to the general public in 1991 via a national network televised cat show held by [[The International Cat Association]] (TICA) in Madison Square Garden.<ref name=\"Helgren2006\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iams.com/pet-health/cat-breeds/munchkin|title=Iams Cat Breed Guide: Munchkin|last=Helgren|first=J. Anne|year=2006|publisher=Telemark Productions|accessdate=29 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318141815/http://www.iams.com/pet-health/cat-breeds/munchkin|archive-date=18 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, the breed would not be officially recognized at that time. Critics predicted that the breed would develop back, hip and leg problems similar to those that plague some Dachshunds.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/07/23/us/a-cat-fight-breaks-out-over-a-breed.html?pagewanted=1|title=A Cat Fight Breaks Out Over a Breed|date=July 23, 1995|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=7 February 2010}}</ref> For many years, the Munchkin breed was not accepted in feline competitions due to the controversial breeding.<ref name=\":0\" /> Dr. Solveig Pflueger, a show judge, [[geneticist]], and Chairperson of TICA's Genetics Committee was a strong advocate for the official recognition of the breed. Pflueger was also a breeder of Munchkin cats herself, having been initially sent two cats from Hochenedel.<ref name=\"NYT\" /> Amidst much controversy, the Munchkin was proposed as a new breed by foundation breeders Laurie Bobskill and Robert Bobskill of Massachusetts and accepted by TICA into its New Breed development program in September 1994. One veteran show judge Katherine Crawford resigned in protest, calling the breed an affront to breeders with ethics.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Helgren98\">{{cite web|url=http://www.petfinder.com/cat-breeds/Munchkin|title=Encyclopedia of Cat Breeds: Munchkin Cat|last=Helgren|first=J. Anne|year=1998|publisher=Barron's Educational Series|accessdate=7 February 2010}}</ref> The Munchkin breed achieved TICA Championship status in May 2003.<ref name=\"TICAintro\" />\n\nCurrently, the only registries that fully recognize the breed are TICA and the [[Southern Africa Cat Council]].\n<ref>https://www.worldcatcongress.org/wp/cat_breed_comp_mus.php</ref> There is controversy among breeders of pedigree cats as to what genetic mutations are abnormal and potentially disadvantageous to the cat.<ref name=\"morris\">{{cite book|title=Catwatching & Catlore|last=Morris|first=Desmond S.|publisher=Arrow Books Ltd.|year=1988|pages=[https://archive.org/details/catwatchingcatlo0000morr/page/183 183&ndash;186]|isbn=0-09-922901-3|url=https://archive.org/details/catwatchingcatlo0000morr/page/183}}</ref> Katie Lisnik, director of cat protection and policy at the [[Humane Society of the United States]], has said \"Breeding animals for exaggerated physical characteristics, particularly when it compromises overall health, is irresponsible\". <ref>https://www.thedodo.com/munchkin-cat-breed-2231333420.html</ref> Several [[Cat registry|cat registries]] do not recognize the Munchkin: [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale F\u00e9line]], which refuses to recognize what they consider a breed based on a \"[[genetic disease]]\", [[achondroplasia]].<ref name=\"FIF\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20071226123710/http://www.fifeweb.org/wp/lib/lib_rls_breg_2007_03.html Breeding and Registration Rules]: 2.7.3 Genetic Diseases. F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale Feline</ref> The [[Governing Council of the Cat Fancy]] likewise refuses to recognize the breed, considering this breed and others like it to be \"unacceptable\" because they are based on an \"abnormal structure or development\".<ref name=\"GCCF\">The Governing Council of the Cat Fancy, [http://www.gccfcats.org/health.html The GCCF says Health Comes First] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150504022515/http://www.gccfcats.org/health.html |date=2015-05-04 }}</ref> The breed is also not recognized by the [[Cat Fanciers' Association]].<ref name=\"CFA\">Cat Fanciers' Association,[http://www.cfa.org/breeds.html CFA Breeds] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629034229/http://www.cfa.org/breeds.html |date=2007-06-29 }}</ref> The Australian Capital Territory (a territory of Australia) government consider the munchkin breed to be \"malformed animals\" and the deliberate breeding of them \"unacceptable\" because of the \"genetic health problems associated with such breeding\".<ref name=\"ACT\">Australian Capital Territory, [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927222247/http://www.tams.act.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0005/12983/Welfare_of_Cats_-_Code_of_Practice.pdf Code of Practice for the Welfare of Cats in the ACT]</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\n[[File:Munchkinshorthaired.jpg|thumb|Munchkin kitten, 7 months old]]\nTICA Standards describe the Munchkin as \"outgoing, intelligent,  and  responds  well  to  being handled\".<ref name=\"TICAstandard\"/> Some sources state that the shortness of their legs does not interfere with their running and leaping abilities,<ref name=\"jonstroud\">{{cite book\n  |last = Stroud\n  |first =Jon\n  |title = The DVD Book of Cats.\n  |publisher = Green Umbrella Pubg\n  |year = 2008}}</ref> while others state their ability to jump is limited by their condition.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[Universities Federation for Animal Welfare]] |title=Munchkin - Limb Deformity |year=2011 |url=https://www.ufaw.org.uk/cats/munchkin-limb-deformity}}</ref>\n\nThe Munchkin has similar characteristics to normal domestic cats, due to their frequent use as [[outcross]]es. It is a small to medium-sized cat with a moderate [[Cat#Body types|body type]] and medium-plush coat. Male Munchkins typically weigh between 6 and 9 pounds (3\u20134&nbsp;kg) and are usually larger than female Munchkins, which typically weigh between 4 and 8 pounds (2\u20133.6&nbsp;kg). The hind legs can be slightly longer than the front which creates a slight rise from the shoulder to the rump. The legs of the Munchkin may be slightly [[Genu varum|bowed]], although excessive bowing is a disqualification in the show ring. [[Cow-hocked]] legs are also penalized.<ref name=\"TICAintro\"/><ref name=\"Helgren2006\"/>\n\nThe Munchkin comes in all coat colors and patterns. It also comes in a long-haired variety, which is shown in a separate Munchkin Longhair category. The short-haired variety has a medium-plush coat while the long-haired has a semi-long silky coat.<ref name=\"TICAintro\"/> TICA rules for outcrossing allows the use of any domestic cat that does not already belong to a recognized breed. Similarity to other breeds is grounds for disqualification. Non-standard Munchkins are not allowed to be shown.<ref name=\"TICAstandard\">{{cite web|url=http://tica.org/pdf/publications/standards/mk.pdf|title=Munchkin Breed Group Standard|date=1 May 2007|publisher=The International Cat Association|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Lilieput, a Munchkin cat from [[Napa, California]], was named the shortest statured living cat in the world by [[Guinness World Records]]. She stands 5.25 inches (13.34 centimeters) tall.<ref name=Yune>{{cite web|last1=Yune|first1=Howard|title=Tiny Napa cat stands tall in new Guinness record book|url=http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/tiny-napa-cat-stands-tall-in-new-guinness-record-book/article_caf78566-a9fa-586f-8868-b427e6ffc8c7.html|website=Napa Valley Register|publisher=Napa Valley Register|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Health==\nIt is still unclear how the mutation impacts the health of the breed. Having only been officially introduced in 1991, the breed is still considered young.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fitzroyvet.com.au/pet-library/munchkin|title=Munchkin breed|last=|first=|date=2015-07-23|website=Fitzroy Vet Hospital VIC|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|quote=however the breed is young having only been introduced to the public as an official breed in 1991.}}</ref> There were early speculations that the Munchkin will develop spinal problems commonly seen in short-legged dog breeds, in 1995 several breeders had their oldest Munchkins [[X-ray|X-rayed]] and examined for signs of joint or bone problems and found none.<ref name=\"Petstyle\">[http://www.petstyle.com/cats/breeds/munchkin Munchkin] PetStyle Lifestyle Network For Pet Lovers. by Twink McCabe {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715071625/http://www.petstyle.com/cats/breeds/munchkin|date=2011-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1995-07-29-1995210005-story.html|title=New cat breed, Munchkin, stands on its stubby legs|last=|first=|authorlink=|date=1995-07-29|website=Baltimore Sun News|publisher=Houston Chronicle|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tampabay.com/archive/1995/06/14/munchkin-fur-is-flying-over-this-rare-cat-breed/|title=Munchkin: Fur is flying over this rare cat breed|last=|first=|date=|website=Tampa Bay Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-06|quote=She X-rayed their joints and bones and found no evidence of crippling. So she began breeding Munchkins}}</ref> \n\nThe genetic mutation causing the short-legged trait in Munchkins is referred to as [[achondroplasia]],<ref name=\"FIF\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/achondroplasia|title=Achondroplasia|last=|first=|date=|website=Genetics Home Reference|publisher=U.S. Department of Health & Human Services|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-14}}</ref> the [[genetic disorder]] that results in [[dwarfism]] and is typically associated with an enlarged head as well as short legs but can also involve symptoms include undersized jaw, thick-looking joints, curved spine, and bow-legged and/or a knock knee posture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.basepaws.com/blog/feline-dwarfism/|title=Feline Dwarfism|last=|first=|date=2019-03-06|website=Basepaws|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-14}}</ref> The condition has sometimes been referred to as [[hypochondroplasia]] or [[pseudoachondroplasia]].<ref name=\"Wedderburn\" /><ref name=\"Messybeast\">[http://www.messybeast.com/gene-anomalies.htm Genetic Abnormalities of Cats]. Messybeast.com Cat Resource</ref> Small [[Litter (animal)|litter]] sizes when two munchkin cats are crossed indicate that [[embryo]]s that are [[homozygous]] for the munchkin gene are non-[[:wikt:viable|viable]].<ref name=\"Messybeast\" />\n\nHowever, there appear to be two conditions with increased incidence in the Munchkin breed: [[lordosis]] (excessive curvature of the spine)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vetinfo.com/munchkin-cat-health-problems.html|title=Munchkin Cat Health Problems|website=VetInfo|access-date=2019-03-24|quote=The Munchkin cat is a very healthy breed with few specific health problems. Munchkin kittens, however, are vulnerable to lordosis, a rare spinal condition in which the spinal muscles grow short, allowing the spine to sink down into the body. Lordosis may be mild or severe, and if it's bad enough, the kitten won't live past three months of age. Many breeders feel that lordosis is a genetic disorder, but it's not specific to the Munchkin cat; many other breeds of cat suffer from lordosis.}}</ref> and [[pectus excavatum]] (hollowed chest).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://catsareontop.com/need-know-munchkin-cats/|title=All You Need to Know About Munchkin Cats|date=2018-01-21|website=Cats Are On Top|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/veterinary-science-and-veterinary-medicine/pectus-excavatum|title=Hereditary and congenital musculoskeletal diseases|last=Hubler|first=M.|last2=Langley-Hobbs|first2=S.J.|date=2009|website=ScienceDirect|publisher=Feline Orthopedic Surgery and Musculoskeletal Disease|access-date=2019-03-24|quote=There may be a familial tendency to thoracic wall deformities (pectus excavatum, unilateral thoracic wall concavity) in Bengal kittens, and chondrodystrophic Munchkin cats may also have an increased incidence of pectus excavatum and spinal lordosis.}}</ref> Both conditions are commonly seen in humans with pseudoachondroplasia.<ref name=\"Wedderburn\">{{cite journal|last=Wedderburn|first=Pete|title=Cat breeds\u2013Trophies with hidden problems|journal=Journal of Small Animal Practice|date=October 2008|volume=49|series=BSAVA Companion|issue=10|pages=7\u20139|doi=10.1111/j.1748-5827.2008.00680.x|quote=This selection for an albeit naturally occurring mutation, resulting in pseudoachondroplasia, has resulted in a breed which appears to have an increased incidence of pectus excavatum and spinal lordosis, both problems commonly seen in human patients with pseudoachondroplasia.}}</ref>\n\n==Genetics==\nThe munchkin gene is [[autosomal]] [[heredity|dominant]].<ref name=\"FIF\"/> [[Homozygous]] embryos for the munchkin gene are not viable , and do not develop in the womb. Only kittens that are [[heterozygous]] for the munchkin gene develop into viable short legged munchkin kittens.<ref name=\"Messybeast\"/> Because only heterozygous(short legged) munchkin cats are able to pass on the gene, all litters with at least one standard (short legged) Munchkin parent have the possibility of containing kittens with the phenotypes: short-legged or normal-legged (referred to as non-standard munchkin), with the genotypes of Mm or mm, where M is the trait for short legs and m is the trait for long legs.  The mating of two munchkin parents, Mm x Mm, have the chance of producing these offspring: 25% MM- a nonviable kitten,  50% Mm-short-legged, 25% mm- normal. The resulting litter will be 2/3 Mm-short-legged and 1/3&nbsp;mm-normal.\n\n[[Punnett square]]s, in which the '''M''' represents the dominant munchkin gene and the '''m''' represents the recessive normal gene, may be used to illustrate the chances of a particular mating resulting in a short-legged cat.\n\nKittens bearing two copies of the munchkin gene ('''MM''') will not develop in the womb.  Kittens bearing one munchkin gene and one normal gene ('''Mm''') will be short-legged munchkins. Kittens bearing two normal genes ('''mm''') will be normal. '''Mm''' munchkin kittens will be able to pass on the munchkin gene to their own offspring. Normal '''mm''' kittens will not, as they do not have a copy of the munchkin gene.\n\n{|\n|\n{| border=1 cellpadding=4 style=\"float:left; clear:right; margin-right:0.5em;\"\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Mating two standard munchkins:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:30%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:3em;\"|\n! style=\"width:3em;\"| M\n! style=\"width:3em;\"| m\n|-\n! M\n| MM\n| Mm\n|-\n! m\n| Mm\n| mm\n|}\n|}\n| {{nowrap|For each kitten conceived from}} this mating, there is a 25% chance it will fail to gestate, a 25% chance it will be normal, and a 50% chance it will be short-legged.\n|}\n\n{|\n| {{nowrap|For each kitten conceived from}} this mating, there is a 0% chance it will be homozygous for the munchkin gene, a 50% chance it will be normal non-standard(long legged) Munchkin, and a 50% chance it will be a standard (short legged) munchkin.{{-}}\n|\n{| border=1 cellpadding=4 style=\"float:right; clear:left; margin-left:0.5em;\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''{{nowrap|Mating a standard or}} {{nowrap|non-standard munchkin}} {{nowrap|with a normal cat:}}'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:30%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:3em;\"|\n! style=\"width:3em;\"| M\n! style=\"width:3em;\"| m\n|-\n! m\n| Mm\n| mm\n|-\n! m\n| Mm\n| mm\n|}\n|}\n|}\n\n==Derived breeds==\nThe Munchkin has been crossed with the curly-coated [[LaPerm]] to create the [[Skookum (cat)|Skookum]], the hairless [[Sphynx (cat)|Sphynx]] to create the [[Minskin]] and [[Bambino (cat)|Bambino]], another curly-coated [[Selkirk Rex]] to create the [[Lambkin (cat)|Lambkin]], the Persian breed group (which includes Himalayans and Exotic Shorthair) to create the [[Napoleon (cat)|Napoleon]], the curled-eared [[American Curl]] to create the [[Kinkalow]], the folded-eared [[Scottish Fold]] to create the [[Scottish Kilts]], and also with the [[Bengal (cat)|Bengal]] to create the Genetta.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dwarf cat]]\n* [[Selective breeding]]\n* [[Squitten]]\n* [[Cat body type genetic mutations]]\n* [[Scottish Fold]], a variety of cat with a gene causing [[osteochondrodysplasia]] rather than [[achondroplasia]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Cat nav}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Munchkin (Cat)}}\n[[Category:Cat breeds]]\n[[Category:Cat breeds originating in the United States]]\n[[Category:Cat breeds and types with short legs]]\n[[Category:Inbred animals]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Catbreed\n<!-- Put article text AFTER this infobox markup. See: -->\n<!-- Wikipedia:WikiProject Cats/Templates for more info.-->\n| name          = Munchkin\n| image         = Longhairedmunchkin.jpg\n| imagecaption  = An adolescent munchkin kitten.\n| altname       =    <!-- separate multiple entries with <br /> -->\n| nickname      =    <!-- separate multiple entries with <br /> -->\n| country       = [[United States]]\n| cfastd        =\n| acfastd       =\n| ticastd       =https://tica.org/phocadownload/mk.pdf\n| ccastd        =\n| acfstd        =\n| gccfstd       =\n| fifestd       =\n| otherstd      =\n| notrecognized =\n| extinct       =\n| note          = \n|}}\n\nThe '''Munchkin cat''' or '''Sausage cat'''<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.peta.org/blog/sausage-cats/|title=\u2018Sausage Cat\u2019 Breed Not Trendy, Just the Result of Cruelty|date=2017-02-10|work=PETA|access-date=2018-07-17|url-status=live|language=en-US}}</ref> is a newer [[breed of cat]] characterized by its [[Dwarf |very short legs]], which are caused by a natural genetic mutation]]. The Munchkin is considered to be the original breed of [[dwarf cat]]. \n\nMuch controversy erupted over the breed when it was recognized by [[The International Cat Association]] (TICA) in 1995 with critics voicing concern over potential health and mobility issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2017/01/31/vets-warn-trend-for-sausage-cats-is-cruel-6416755/|title=Vets warn trend for sausage cats is cruel|last=|first=|date=2017-01-31|website=Metro UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> [[Governing Council of the Cat Fancy]] has not recognized it as a [[standardised breed]].\n\nThe name \"[[munchkin]]\" derives from writer [[L. Frank Baum]]'s diminutive inhabitants of [[Munchkin Country]], originating in the 1900 novel, ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Munchkin & Midget Cat Breed Facts|url=https://www.petmd.com/cat/breeds/c_ct_munchkin|website=www.petmd.com|publisher=petMD, LLC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Nunn|first1=Lyn|title=Munchkin Cats - Origin and History|url=http://www.catbreedsjunction.com/munchkin-cats.html|website=Cat Breeds Junction|accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fawcett|first1=Kirstin|title=7 Short Facts About Munchkin Cats|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/80011/7-short-facts-about-munchkin-cats|website=[[Mental Floss]]|accessdate=8 December 2017|language=en|date=3 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n=== Breed creation ===\nShort-legged cats have been documented a number of times around the world since the 1940s. A British veterinary report in 1944 noted four generations of short-legged cats which were similar to normal cats except for the length of the legs. This line disappeared during the Second World War but other short-legged cats were spotted in Russia during 1956 and the United States in the 1970s.<ref name=\"TICAintro\">{{cite web|url=https://tica.org/munchkin-breeders?view=article&id=857:munchkin-breed&catid=79|title=Munchkin Breed|date=13 August 2018|website=The International Cat Association (TICA)|publisher=The International Cat Association (TICA)|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, Sandra Hochenedel, a music teacher in [[Rayville, Louisiana|Rayville]], [[Louisiana]], found two pregnant cats who had been chased under a truck by a dog.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=coXIF8WbEKEC&dq|title=100 Cats Who Changed Civilization: History's Most Influential Felines|last=Stall|first=Sam|publisher=Quirk Books|year=2007|isbn=9781594741630|location=Philadelphia, PA|pages=20\u201322|via=Google Books}}</ref> She kept one of the cats and named her Blackberry and half of her kittens were born short-legged. Hochenedel gave a short-legged male kitten from one of Blackberry's litters to a friend, Kay LaFrance of [[Monroe, Louisiana|Monroe]], Louisiana, and she named the kitten Toulouse.<ref name=\":0\" /> It is from Blackberry and Toulouse's litter that today's Munchkin breed is descended.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Registry history of Munchkin breed ===\nThe Munchkin cat was first introduced to the general public in 1991 via a national network televised cat show held by [[The International Cat Association]] (TICA) in Madison Square Garden.<ref name=\"Helgren2006\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iams.com/pet-health/cat-breeds/munchkin|title=Iams Cat Breed Guide: Munchkin|last=Helgren|first=J. Anne|year=2006|publisher=Telemark Productions|accessdate=29 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318141815/http://www.iams.com/pet-health/cat-breeds/munchkin|archive-date=18 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, the breed would not be officially recognized at that time. Critics predicted that the breed would develop back, hip and leg problems similar to those that plague some Dachshunds.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/07/23/us/a-cat-fight-breaks-out-over-a-breed.html?pagewanted=1|title=A Cat Fight Breaks Out Over a Breed|date=July 23, 1995|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=7 February 2010}}</ref> For many years, the Munchkin breed was not accepted in feline competitions due to the controversial breeding.<ref name=\":0\" /> Dr. Solveig Pflueger, a show judge, [[geneticist]], and Chairperson of TICA's Genetics Committee was a strong advocate for the official recognition of the breed. Pflueger was also a breeder of Munchkin cats herself, having been initially sent two cats from Hochenedel.<ref name=\"NYT\" /> Amidst much controversy, the Munchkin was proposed as a new breed by foundation breeders Laurie Bobskill and Robert Bobskill of Massachusetts and accepted by TICA into its New Breed development program in September 1994. One veteran show judge Katherine Crawford resigned in protest, calling the breed an affront to breeders with ethics.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Helgren98\">{{cite web|url=http://www.petfinder.com/cat-breeds/Munchkin|title=Encyclopedia of Cat Breeds: Munchkin Cat|last=Helgren|first=J. Anne|year=1998|publisher=Barron's Educational Series|accessdate=7 February 2010}}</ref> The Munchkin breed achieved TICA Championship status in May 2003.<ref name=\"TICAintro\" />\n\nCurrently, the only registries that fully recognize the breed are TICA and the [[Southern Africa Cat Council]].\n<ref>https://www.worldcatcongress.org/wp/cat_breed_comp_mus.php</ref> There is controversy among breeders of pedigree cats as to what genetic mutations are abnormal and potentially disadvantageous to the cat.<ref name=\"morris\">{{cite book|title=Catwatching & Catlore|last=Morris|first=Desmond S.|publisher=Arrow Books Ltd.|year=1988|pages=[https://archive.org/details/catwatchingcatlo0000morr/page/183 183&ndash;186]|isbn=0-09-922901-3|url=https://archive.org/details/catwatchingcatlo0000morr/page/183}}</ref> Katie Lisnik, director of cat protection and policy at the [[Humane Society of the United States]], has said \"Breeding animals for exaggerated physical characteristics, particularly when it compromises overall health, is irresponsible\". <ref>https://www.thedodo.com/munchkin-cat-breed-2231333420.html</ref> Several [[Cat registry|cat registries]] do not recognize the Munchkin: [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale F\u00e9line]], which refuses to recognize what they consider a breed based on a \"[[genetic disease]]\", [[achondroplasia]].<ref name=\"FIF\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20071226123710/http://www.fifeweb.org/wp/lib/lib_rls_breg_2007_03.html Breeding and Registration Rules]: 2.7.3 Genetic Diseases. F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale Feline</ref> The [[Governing Council of the Cat Fancy]] likewise refuses to recognize the breed, considering this breed and others like it to be \"unacceptable\" because they are based on an \"abnormal structure or development\".<ref name=\"GCCF\">The Governing Council of the Cat Fancy, [http://www.gccfcats.org/health.html The GCCF says Health Comes First] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150504022515/http://www.gccfcats.org/health.html |date=2015-05-04 }}</ref> The breed is also not recognized by the [[Cat Fanciers' Association]].<ref name=\"CFA\">Cat Fanciers' Association,[http://www.cfa.org/breeds.html CFA Breeds] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629034229/http://www.cfa.org/breeds.html |date=2007-06-29 }}</ref> The Australian Capital Territory (a territory of Australia) government consider the munchkin breed to be \"malformed animals\" and the deliberate breeding of them \"unacceptable\" because of the \"genetic health problems associated with such breeding\".<ref name=\"ACT\">Australian Capital Territory, [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927222247/http://www.tams.act.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0005/12983/Welfare_of_Cats_-_Code_of_Practice.pdf Code of Practice for the Welfare of Cats in the ACT]</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\n[[File:Munchkinshorthaired.jpg|thumb|Munchkin kitten, 7 months old]]\nTICA Standards describe the Munchkin as \"outgoing, intelligent,  and  responds  well  to  being handled\".<ref name=\"TICAstandard\"/> Some sources state that the shortness of their legs does not interfere with their running and leaping abilities,<ref name=\"jonstroud\">{{cite book\n  |last = Stroud\n  |first =Jon\n  |title = The DVD Book of Cats.\n  |publisher = Green Umbrella Pubg\n  |year = 2008}}</ref> while others state their ability to jump is limited by their condition.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[Universities Federation for Animal Welfare]] |title=Munchkin - Limb Deformity |year=2011 |url=https://www.ufaw.org.uk/cats/munchkin-limb-deformity}}</ref>\n\nThe Munchkin has similar characteristics to normal domestic cats, due to their frequent use as [[outcross]]es. It is a small to medium-sized cat with a moderate [[Cat#Body types|body type]] and medium-plush coat. Male Munchkins typically weigh between 6 and 9 pounds (3\u20134&nbsp;kg) and are usually larger than female Munchkins, which typically weigh between 4 and 8 pounds (2\u20133.6&nbsp;kg). The hind legs can be slightly longer than the front which creates a slight rise from the shoulder to the rump. The legs of the Munchkin may be slightly [[Genu varum|bowed]], although excessive bowing is a disqualification in the show ring. [[Cow-hocked]] legs are also penalized.<ref name=\"TICAintro\"/><ref name=\"Helgren2006\"/>\n\nThe Munchkin comes in all coat colors and patterns. It also comes in a long-haired variety, which is shown in a separate Munchkin Longhair category. The short-haired variety has a medium-plush coat while the long-haired has a semi-long silky coat.<ref name=\"TICAintro\"/> TICA rules for outcrossing allows the use of any domestic cat that does not already belong to a recognized breed. Similarity to other breeds is grounds for disqualification. Non-standard Munchkins are not allowed to be shown.<ref name=\"TICAstandard\">{{cite web|url=http://tica.org/pdf/publications/standards/mk.pdf|title=Munchkin Breed Group Standard|date=1 May 2007|publisher=The International Cat Association|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Lilieput, a Munchkin cat from [[Napa, California]], was named the shortest statured living cat in the world by [[Guinness World Records]]. She stands 5.25 inches (13.34 centimeters) tall.<ref name=Yune>{{cite web|last1=Yune|first1=Howard|title=Tiny Napa cat stands tall in new Guinness record book|url=http://napavalleyregister.com/news/local/tiny-napa-cat-stands-tall-in-new-guinness-record-book/article_caf78566-a9fa-586f-8868-b427e6ffc8c7.html|website=Napa Valley Register|publisher=Napa Valley Register|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Health==\nIt is still unclear how the mutation impacts the health of the breed. Having only been officially introduced in 1991, the breed is still considered young.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fitzroyvet.com.au/pet-library/munchkin|title=Munchkin breed|last=|first=|date=2015-07-23|website=Fitzroy Vet Hospital VIC|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|quote=however the breed is young having only been introduced to the public as an official breed in 1991.}}</ref> There were early speculations that the Munchkin will develop spinal problems commonly seen in short-legged dog breeds, in 1995 several breeders had their oldest Munchkins [[X-ray|X-rayed]] and examined for signs of joint or bone problems and found none.<ref name=\"Petstyle\">[http://www.petstyle.com/cats/breeds/munchkin Munchkin] PetStyle Lifestyle Network For Pet Lovers. by Twink McCabe {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715071625/http://www.petstyle.com/cats/breeds/munchkin|date=2011-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1995-07-29-1995210005-story.html|title=New cat breed, Munchkin, stands on its stubby legs|last=|first=|authorlink=|date=1995-07-29|website=Baltimore Sun News|publisher=Houston Chronicle|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tampabay.com/archive/1995/06/14/munchkin-fur-is-flying-over-this-rare-cat-breed/|title=Munchkin: Fur is flying over this rare cat breed|last=|first=|date=|website=Tampa Bay Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-06|quote=She X-rayed their joints and bones and found no evidence of crippling. So she began breeding Munchkins}}</ref> \n\nThe genetic mutation causing the short-legged trait in Munchkins is referred to as [[achondroplasia]],<ref name=\"FIF\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/achondroplasia|title=Achondroplasia|last=|first=|date=|website=Genetics Home Reference|publisher=U.S. Department of Health & Human Services|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-14}}</ref> the [[genetic disorder]] that results in [[dwarfism]] and is typically associated with an enlarged head as well as short legs but can also involve symptoms include undersized jaw, thick-looking joints, curved spine, and bow-legged and/or a knock knee posture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.basepaws.com/blog/feline-dwarfism/|title=Feline Dwarfism|last=|first=|date=2019-03-06|website=Basepaws|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-14}}</ref> The condition has sometimes been referred to as [[hypochondroplasia]] or [[pseudoachondroplasia]].<ref name=\"Wedderburn\" /><ref name=\"Messybeast\">[http://www.messybeast.com/gene-anomalies.htm Genetic Abnormalities of Cats]. Messybeast.com Cat Resource</ref> Small [[Litter (animal)|litter]] sizes when two munchkin cats are crossed indicate that [[embryo]]s that are [[homozygous]] for the munchkin gene are non-[[:wikt:viable|viable]].<ref name=\"Messybeast\" />\n\nHowever, there appear to be two conditions with increased incidence in the Munchkin breed: [[lordosis]] (excessive curvature of the spine)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vetinfo.com/munchkin-cat-health-problems.html|title=Munchkin Cat Health Problems|website=VetInfo|access-date=2019-03-24|quote=The Munchkin cat is a very healthy breed with few specific health problems. Munchkin kittens, however, are vulnerable to lordosis, a rare spinal condition in which the spinal muscles grow short, allowing the spine to sink down into the body. Lordosis may be mild or severe, and if it's bad enough, the kitten won't live past three months of age. Many breeders feel that lordosis is a genetic disorder, but it's not specific to the Munchkin cat; many other breeds of cat suffer from lordosis.}}</ref> and [[pectus excavatum]] (hollowed chest).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://catsareontop.com/need-know-munchkin-cats/|title=All You Need to Know About Munchkin Cats|date=2018-01-21|website=Cats Are On Top|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/veterinary-science-and-veterinary-medicine/pectus-excavatum|title=Hereditary and congenital musculoskeletal diseases|last=Hubler|first=M.|last2=Langley-Hobbs|first2=S.J.|date=2009|website=ScienceDirect|publisher=Feline Orthopedic Surgery and Musculoskeletal Disease|access-date=2019-03-24|quote=There may be a familial tendency to thoracic wall deformities (pectus excavatum, unilateral thoracic wall concavity) in Bengal kittens, and chondrodystrophic Munchkin cats may also have an increased incidence of pectus excavatum and spinal lordosis.}}</ref> Both conditions are commonly seen in humans with pseudoachondroplasia.<ref name=\"Wedderburn\">{{cite journal|last=Wedderburn|first=Pete|title=Cat breeds\u2013Trophies with hidden problems|journal=Journal of Small Animal Practice|date=October 2008|volume=49|series=BSAVA Companion|issue=10|pages=7\u20139|doi=10.1111/j.1748-5827.2008.00680.x|quote=This selection for an albeit naturally occurring mutation, resulting in pseudoachondroplasia, has resulted in a breed which appears to have an increased incidence of pectus excavatum and spinal lordosis, both problems commonly seen in human patients with pseudoachondroplasia.}}</ref>\n\n==Genetics==\nThe munchkin gene is [[autosomal]] [[heredity|dominant]].<ref name=\"FIF\"/> [[Homozygous]] embryos for the munchkin gene are not viable , and do not develop in the womb. Only kittens that are [[heterozygous]] for the munchkin gene develop into viable short legged munchkin kittens.<ref name=\"Messybeast\"/> Because only heterozygous(short legged) munchkin cats are able to pass on the gene, all litters with at least one standard (short legged) Munchkin parent have the possibility of containing kittens with the phenotypes: short-legged or normal-legged (referred to as non-standard munchkin), with the genotypes of Mm or mm, where M is the trait for short legs and m is the trait for long legs.  The mating of two munchkin parents, Mm x Mm, have the chance of producing these offspring: 25% MM- a nonviable kitten,  50% Mm-short-legged, 25% mm- normal. The resulting litter will be 2/3 Mm-short-legged and 1/3&nbsp;mm-normal.\n\n[[Punnett square]]s, in which the '''M''' represents the dominant munchkin gene and the '''m''' represents the recessive normal gene, may be used to illustrate the chances of a particular mating resulting in a short-legged cat.\n\nKittens bearing two copies of the munchkin gene ('''MM''') will not develop in the womb.  Kittens bearing one munchkin gene and one normal gene ('''Mm''') will be short-legged munchkins. Kittens bearing two normal genes ('''mm''') will be normal. '''Mm''' munchkin kittens will be able to pass on the munchkin gene to their own offspring. Normal '''mm''' kittens will not, as they do not have a copy of the munchkin gene.\n\n{|\n|\n{| border=1 cellpadding=4 style=\"float:left; clear:right; margin-right:0.5em;\"\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Mating two standard munchkins:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:30%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:3em;\"|\n! style=\"width:3em;\"| M\n! style=\"width:3em;\"| m\n|-\n! M\n| MM\n| Mm\n|-\n! m\n| Mm\n| mm\n|}\n|}\n| {{nowrap|For each kitten conceived from}} this mating, there is a 25% chance it will fail to gestate, a 25% chance it will be normal, and a 50% chance it will be short-legged.\n|}\n\n{|\n| {{nowrap|For each kitten conceived from}} this mating, there is a 0% chance it will be homozygous for the munchkin gene, a 50% chance it will be normal non-standard(long legged) Munchkin, and a 50% chance it will be a standard (short legged) munchkin.{{-}}\n|\n{| border=1 cellpadding=4 style=\"float:right; clear:left; margin-left:0.5em;\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''{{nowrap|Mating a standard or}} {{nowrap|non-standard munchkin}} {{nowrap|with a normal cat:}}'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:30%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:3em;\"|\n! style=\"width:3em;\"| M\n! style=\"width:3em;\"| m\n|-\n! m\n| Mm\n| mm\n|-\n! m\n| Mm\n| mm\n|}\n|}\n|}\n\n==Derived breeds==\nThe Munchkin has been crossed with the curly-coated [[LaPerm]] to create the [[Skookum (cat)|Skookum]], the hairless [[Sphynx (cat)|Sphynx]] to create the [[Minskin]] and [[Bambino (cat)|Bambino]], another curly-coated [[Selkirk Rex]] to create the [[Lambkin (cat)|Lambkin]], the Persian breed group (which includes Himalayans and Exotic Shorthair) to create the [[Napoleon (cat)|Napoleon]], the curled-eared [[American Curl]] to create the [[Kinkalow]], the folded-eared [[Scottish Fold]] to create the [[Scottish Kilts]], and also with the [[Bengal (cat)|Bengal]] to create the Genetta.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dwarf cat]]\n* [[Selective breeding]]\n* [[Squitten]]\n* [[Cat body type genetic mutations]]\n* [[Scottish Fold]], a variety of cat with a gene causing [[osteochondrodysplasia]] rather than [[achondroplasia]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Cat nav}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Munchkin (Cat)}}\n[[Category:Cat breeds]]\n[[Category:Cat breeds originating in the United States]]\n[[Category:Cat breeds and types with short legs]]\n[[Category:Inbred animals]]\n", "name_user": "Maria Sieglinda von Nudeldorf", "label": "safe", "comment": "[[", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Munchkin_cat"}
{"title_page": "1921 Swedish general election", "text_new": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 1921 Swedish general election\n| country = Sweden\n| type = parliamentary\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 1920 Swedish general election\n| previous_year = 1920\n| next_election = 1924 Swedish general election\n| next_year = 1924\n| seats_for_election = All 230 seats in the [[Parliament of Sweden|Riksdag]]\n| election_date = 10 September 1921\n| image1 = [[File:Hjalmar branting stor bild.jpg|170x170px]]\n| leader1 = [[Hjalmar Branting]]\n| party1 = Swedish Social Democratic Party\n| alliance1 = \n| last_election1 = 75\n| seats1 = 93\n| seat_change1 = {{increase}}18\n| popular_vote1 = 630,855\n| percentage1 = 36.2%\n| image2 = [[File:Arvid Lindman.jpg|170x170px]]\n| leader2 = [[Arvid Lindman]]\n| party2 = General Electoral League\n| alliance2 = \n| last_election2 = 71\n| seats2 = 62\n| seat_change2 = {{decrease}}9\n| popular_vote2 = 449,302\n| percentage2 = 25.8%\n| image3 = [[File:Raoul Hamilton 1959.JPG|170x170px]]\n| leader3 = [[Raoul Hamilton]]\n| party3 = Free-minded National Association\n| alliance3 = \n| last_election3 = 47\n| seats3 = 41\n| seat_change3 = {{decrease}}6\n| popular_vote3 = 325,608\n| percentage3 = 18.7%\n| leader4 = [[Johan Andersson i Rakl\u00f6sen|Johan Andersson]]\n| party4 = Farmers' League (Sweden)\n| last_election4 = 30<ref>Total seats of Farmers' League and [[National Farmers' Association (Sweden)|Farmers' Association]]</ref>\n| seats4 = 21\n| seat_change4 = {{decrease}}9\n| popular_vote4 = 192,269\n| percentage4 = 11.0%\n| image5 = [[File:Karl Kilbom - Sveriges styresm\u00e4n.jpg|170x170px]]\n| leader5 = [[Karl Kilbom]]\n| party5 = Communist Party of Sweden (1921-1967)\n| last_election5 = 7<ref>As [[Social Democratic Left Party of Sweden|Social Democratic Left]]</ref>\n| seats5 = 7\n| seat_change5 = {{steady}}0\n| popular_vote5 = 80,355\n| percentage5 = 4.6%\n| image6 = [[File:Ivar Vennerstr\u00f6m - Sveriges styresm\u00e4n.jpg|170x170px]]\n| leader6 = [[Ivar Vennerstr\u00f6m]]\n| party6 = Social Democratic Left Party of Sweden (1921)\n| last_election6 = '''New'''\n| seats6 = 6\n| seat_change6 = {{increase}}6\n| popular_vote6 = 56,241\n| percentage6 = 3.2%\n| title = [[Prime Minister of Sweden|Prime Minister]]\n| posttitle = PM-elect\n| before_election = [[Oscar von Sydow]]\n| before_party = Independent (politician)\n| after_election = [[Hjalmar Branting]]\n| after_party = Swedish Social Democratic Party\n}}\n\nEarly '''general elections''' were held in [[Sweden]] between 10 and 26 September 1921.<ref name=NS>[[Dieter Nohlen|Nohlen, D]] & St\u00f6ver, P (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', p1858 {{ISBN|978-3-8329-5609-7}}</ref> In the first elections held under [[universal suffrage]], the [[Swedish Social Democratic Party]] remained the largest party, winning 93 of the 230 seats in the Second Chamber of the [[Parliament of Sweden|Riksdag]]. Party leader [[Hjalmar Branting]] formed his [[Branting II (government)|second government]].\n\n==Background==\nBefore the elections in 1921, the [[Left Party (Sweden)|Social Democratic Left Party of Sweden]] accepted [[Lenin's April Theses]]. It was renamed the [[Left Party (Sweden)|Communist Party of Sweden]], whilst a breakaway faction of some 6,000 socialists who had been excluded by the communists as ''non-revolutionary elements'' kept the [[Social Democratic Left Party of Sweden (1921)|previous name]].\n\n==Electoral system==\nIn 1921, a universal and equal [[universal suffrage|suffrage]] was introduced for men and women alike, and the Riksdag finally achieved a system of democratic representation for all [[citizen]]s who were at least 23 years old on election day. Nevertheless, it was still possible, even after 1921, to exclude certain groups from the right to vote. An example was individuals who had been declared incapable of managing their own affairs by a court of law. This limitation of the franchise disappeared only in 1989 when the Riksdag abolished [[incapacitation (penology)|incapacitation]].\n\nIt signified the five first women MPS to be elected to the Swedish Parliament after the women suffrage of 1919, with [[Kerstin Hesselgren]] in the Upper chamber, and [[Nelly Th\u00fcring]] (Social Democrat), [[Agda \u00d6stlund]] (Social Democrat) [[Elisabeth Tamm]] (liberal) and [[Bertha Wellin]] (Conservative) in the Lower chamber.\n\nAlongside the universal franchise reform, a [[Parliamentarism|parliamentary system of government]] developed and gained acceptance, implying that the government requires the Riksdag's confidence and support for all major decisions. As of 1921, all major treaties with foreign states had to be approved by the Riksdag, and the two chambers of the Riksdag now elected their own [[speaker (politics)|Speakers]] along with two deputy speakers each.\n\n==Results==\n{{main|Results of the 1921 Swedish general election}}\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:right\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n!Seats\n!+/\u2013\n|-\n|align=left|[[Swedish Social Democratic Party|Social Democratic Party]]||630,855||36.2||93||+18\n|-\n|align=left|[[Moderate Party|General Electoral League]]||449,302||25.8||62||\u20139\n|-\n|align=left|[[Free-minded National Association]]||325,608||18.7||41||\u20136\n|-\n|align=left|[[Centre Party (Sweden)|Farmers' League]]||192,269||11.0||21||\u20139\n|-\n|align=left|[[Left Party (Sweden)|Communist Party of Sweden|Communist Party]]||80,355||4.6||7||0\n|-\n|align=left|[[Social Democratic Left Party of Sweden (1921)Social Democratic Left Party]]||56,241||3.2||6||New\n|-\n|align=left|Other parties||7,322||0.4||0||0\n|-\n|align=left|Invalid/blank votes||5,601||\u2013||\u2013||\u2013\n|-\n|align=left|'''Total'''||'''1,747,553'''||'''100'''||'''230'''||'''0'''\n|-\n|align=left|Registered voters/turnout||3,222,917||54.2||\u2013||\u2013\n|-\n|align=left colspan=5|Source: Nohlen & St\u00f6ver\n|}\n{{Bar box\n|title=Popular vote\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|width=600px\n|barwidth=350px\n|bars=\n{{Bar percent|S|{{Swedish Social Democratic Party/meta/color}}|36.22}}\n{{Bar percent|AV|{{Moderate Party/meta/color}}|25.79}}\n{{Bar percent|FL|{{Liberals (Sweden)/meta/color}}|18.69}}\n{{Bar percent|B|{{Centre Party (Sweden)/meta/color}}|11.04}}\n{{Bar percent|SKP|{{Left Party (Sweden)/meta/color}}|4.61}}\n{{Bar percent|SSV|#E53333|3.23}}\n{{Bar percent|Others|{{Other/meta/color}}|0.42}}\n}}\n{{Bar box\n|title=Parliament seats\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|width=600px\n|barwidth=350px\n|bars=\n{{Bar percent|S|{{Swedish Social Democratic Party/meta/color}}|40.43}}\n{{Bar percent|AV|{{Moderate Party/meta/color}}|26.96}}\n{{Bar percent|FL|{{Liberals (Sweden)/meta/color}}|17.83}}\n{{Bar percent|B|{{Centre Party (Sweden)/meta/color}}|9.13}}\n{{Bar percent|SKP|{{Left Party (Sweden)/meta/color}}|3.04}}\n{{Bar percent|SSV|#E53333|2.61}}\n}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nAs a result of the election Prime Minister [[Oscar von Sydow]] resigned and was replaced by [[Hjalmar Branting]] who also became [[Foreign Minister of Sweden]] .\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*''[[Nordisk familjebok]]'', (''Owl edition''), 2nd ed., Stockholm : Nordisk familjeboks f\u00f6rlags aktiebolag, 1904-1926 {{in lang|sv}}\n\n{{Swedish elections}}\n\n[[Category:General elections in Sweden|1921]]\n[[Category:1921 elections in Europe]]\n[[Category:1921 in Sweden]]\n[[Category:September 1921 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 1921 Swedish general election\n| country = Sweden\n| type = parliamentary\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 1920 Swedish general election\n| previous_year = 1920\n| next_election = 1924 Swedish general election\n| next_year = 1924\n| seats_for_election = All 230 seats in the [[Parliament of Sweden|Riksdag]]\n| election_date = 10 September 1921\n| image1 = [[File:Hjalmar branting stor bild.jpg|170x170px]]\n| leader1 = [[Hjalmar Branting]]\n| party1 = Swedish Social Democratic Party\n| alliance1 = \n| last_election1 = 75\n| seats1 = 93\n| seat_change1 = {{increase}}18\n| popular_vote1 = 630,855\n| percentage1 = 36.2%\n| image2 = [[File:Arvid Lindman.jpg|170x170px]]\n| leader2 = [[Arvid Lindman]]\n| party2 = General Electoral League\n| alliance2 = \n| last_election2 = 71\n| seats2 = 62\n| seat_change2 = {{decrease}}9\n| popular_vote2 = 449,302\n| percentage2 = 25.8%\n| image3 = [[File:Raoul Hamilton 1959.JPG|170x170px]]\n| leader3 = [[Raoul Hamilton]]\n| party3 = Free-minded National Association\n| alliance3 = \n| last_election3 = 47\n| seats3 = 41\n| seat_change3 = {{decrease}}6\n| popular_vote3 = 325,608\n| percentage3 = 18.7%\n| leader4 = [[Johan Andersson i Rakl\u00f6sen|Johan Andersson]]\n| party4 = Farmers' League (Sweden)\n| last_election4 = 30<ref>Total seats of Farmers' League and [[National Farmers' Association (Sweden)|Farmers' Association]]</ref>\n| seats4 = 21\n| seat_change4 = {{decrease}}9\n| popular_vote4 = 192,269\n| percentage4 = 11.0%\n| image5 = [[File:Karl Kilbom - Sveriges styresm\u00e4n.jpg|170x170px]]\n| leader5 = [[Karl Kilbom]]\n| party5 = Communist Party of Sweden (1921-1967)\n| last_election5 = 7<ref>As [[Social Democratic Left Party of Sweden|Social Democratic Left]]</ref>\n| seats5 = 7\n| seat_change5 = {{steady}}0\n| popular_vote5 = 80,355\n| percentage5 = 4.6%\n| image6 = [[File:Ivar Vennerstr\u00f6m - Sveriges styresm\u00e4n.jpg|170x170px]]\n| leader6 = [[Ivar Vennerstr\u00f6m]]\n| party6 = Social Democratic Left Party of Sweden (1921)\n| last_election6 = '''New'''\n| seats6 = 6\n| seat_change6 = {{increase}}6\n| popular_vote6 = 56,241\n| percentage6 = 3.2%\n| title = [[Prime Minister of Sweden|Prime Minister]]\n| posttitle = PM-elect\n| before_election = [[Oscar von Sydow]]\n| before_party = Independent (politician)\n| after_election = [[Hjalmar Branting]]\n| after_party = Swedish Social Democratic Party\n}}\n\nEarly '''general elections''' were held in [[Sweden]] between 10 and 26 September 1921.<ref name=NS>[[Dieter Nohlen|Nohlen, D]] & St\u00f6ver, P (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', p1858 {{ISBN|978-3-8329-5609-7}}</ref> In the first elections held under [[universal suffrage]], the [[Swedish Social Democratic Party]] remained the largest party, winning 93 of the 230 seats in the Second Chamber of the [[Parliament of Sweden|Riksdag]]. Party leader [[Hjalmar Branting]] formed his [[Branting II (government)|second government]].\n\n==Background==\nBefore the elections in 1921, the [[Left Party (Sweden)|Social Democratic Left Party of Sweden]] accepted [[Lenin's April Theses]]. It was renamed the [[Left Party (Sweden)|Communist Party of Sweden]], whilst a breakaway faction of some 6,000 socialists who had been excluded by the communists as ''non-revolutionary elements'' kept the [[Social Democratic Left Party of Sweden (1921)|previous name]].\n\n==Electoral system==\nIn 1921, a universal and equal [[universal suffrage|suffrage]] was introduced for men and women alike, and the Riksdag finally achieved a system of democratic representation for all [[citizen]]s who were at least 23 years old on election day. Nevertheless, it was still possible, even after 1921, to exclude certain groups from the right to vote. An example was individuals who had been declared incapable of managing their own affairs by a court of law. This limitation of the franchise disappeared only in 1989 when the Riksdag abolished [[incapacitation (penology)|incapacitation]].\n\nIt signified the five first women MPS to be elected to the Swedish Parliament after the women suffrage of 1919, with [[Kerstin Hesselgren]] in the Upper chamber, and [[Nelly Th\u00fcring]] (Social Democrat), [[Agda \u00d6stlund]] (Social Democrat) [[Elisabeth Tamm]] (liberal) and [[Bertha Wellin]] (Conservative) in the Lower chamber.\n\nAlongside the universal franchise reform, a [[Parliamentarism|parliamentary system of government]] developed and gained acceptance, implying that the government requires the Riksdag's confidence and support for all major decisions. As of 1921, all major treaties with foreign states had to be approved by the Riksdag, and the two chambers of the Riksdag now elected their own [[speaker (politics)|Speakers]] along with two deputy speakers each.\n\n==Results==\n{{main|Results of the 1921 Swedish general election}}\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:right\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n!Seats\n!+/\u2013\n|-\n|align=left|[[Swedish Social Democratic Party|Social Democratic Party]]||630,855||36.2||93||+18\n|-\n|align=left|[[Moderate Party|General Electoral League]]||449,302||25.8||62||\u20139\n|-\n|align=left|[[Free-minded National Association]]||325,608||18.7||41||\u20136\n|-\n|align=left|[[Centre Party (Sweden)|Farmers' League]]||192,269||11.0||21||\u20139\n|-\n|align=left|[[Left Party (Sweden)|Communist Party of Sweden|Communist Party]]||80,355||4.6||7||0\n|-\n|align=left|[[Social Democratic Left Party of Sweden (1921)|Social Democratic Left Party of Sweden|Social Democratic Left Party]]||56,241||3.2||6||New\n|-\n|align=left|Other parties||7,322||0.4||0||0\n|-\n|align=left|Invalid/blank votes||5,601||\u2013||\u2013||\u2013\n|-\n|align=left|'''Total'''||'''1,747,553'''||'''100'''||'''230'''||'''0'''\n|-\n|align=left|Registered voters/turnout||3,222,917||54.2||\u2013||\u2013\n|-\n|align=left colspan=5|Source: Nohlen & St\u00f6ver\n|}\n{{Bar box\n|title=Popular vote\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|width=600px\n|barwidth=350px\n|bars=\n{{Bar percent|S|{{Swedish Social Democratic Party/meta/color}}|36.22}}\n{{Bar percent|AV|{{Moderate Party/meta/color}}|25.79}}\n{{Bar percent|FL|{{Liberals (Sweden)/meta/color}}|18.69}}\n{{Bar percent|B|{{Centre Party (Sweden)/meta/color}}|11.04}}\n{{Bar percent|SKP|{{Left Party (Sweden)/meta/color}}|4.61}}\n{{Bar percent|SSV|#E53333|3.23}}\n{{Bar percent|Others|{{Other/meta/color}}|0.42}}\n}}\n{{Bar box\n|title=Parliament seats\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|width=600px\n|barwidth=350px\n|bars=\n{{Bar percent|S|{{Swedish Social Democratic Party/meta/color}}|40.43}}\n{{Bar percent|AV|{{Moderate Party/meta/color}}|26.96}}\n{{Bar percent|FL|{{Liberals (